February 19th, 2021

1. Download FASTQ files.

My FASTQ files are from the Integrated Genomics Operations (IGO) core at MSK. I generated these data in the laboratory of Dr. Yael David at MSK. These are HEK293T cells, wildtpye (WT) expressing endogenous SHPRH and SHPRH KO cells in which I used CRISPR/Cas9 technologies to develop a stable SHPRH knockout cell line. I submitted the cells as flash-frozen pellets harvested in PBS in triplicate (9 samples). IGO extracted the RNA, performed QC, and library prep using IDT Dual Index adapters. Libraries were sequences on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 with 50 bp paired-end reads and 30-40 million reads per sample.

In terms of my experimental conditions, I am particularly interested in characterizing the effects of knocking out SHPRH (Snf2-histone linker-PHD-RING-helicase). I made two monoclonal knockout cell lines, clone 2D9 and 2D10, in HEK293T cells. I also developed a monoclonal WT SHPRH cell line in HEK 293T cells, clone 2C11.

Loading files

I first had to log into the IGO MSK server and load the files into my scratch folder.

cd /Volumes/Davidshy/Project_11231_B
rsync -ar --progress Project_11231_B ifa4001@aphrodite.med.cornell.edu:/athena/angsd/scratch/ifa4001/

2. Align the FASTQ file with an appropriate aligner (you may have to build a new index). Document parameters, summary of outcome, and basic QC. (3pt)

Before moving forward with the alignment, I must first index the human genome and run fastqc on the raw data files.

I picked one file to run fastqc, SHPRH_KO_2D10_1.

spack load fastqc
fastqc RNAseq_IA_fastq/HEK293T_SHPRH_KO_2D10_1_R1_001.fastq.gz --extract

Build human genome index

To create the genome index,I downloaded the human genome and annotation in /project/human_STARindex.

wget -O human.fa.gz "ftp://ftp.ebi.ac.uk/pub/databases/gencode/Gencode_human/release_37/gencode.v37.annotation.gtf.gz"
wget -O human.gtf.gz "ftp://ftp.ebi.ac.uk/pub/databases/gencode/Gencode_human/release_37/gencode.v37.transcripts.fa.gz"
gunzip human.fa.gz
gunzip human.gtf.gz
chmod +rwx human.fa
chmod +rwx human.gtf

Next, I generated the STAR index

mkdir human_STARindex
touch chrName.txt
chmod +rwx human_STARindex
chmod +rwx chrName.txt
#! /bin/bash -l
#SBATCH --partition=angsd_class
#SBATCH --nodes=2
#SBATCH --ntasks=4
#SBATCH --job-name=human_indexing
#SBATCH --time=12:00:00
#SBATCH --mem=50G
spack load star@2.7.0e
STAR --runMode genomeGenerate \
     --runThreadN 4 \
     --genomeDir /scratchLocal/ifa4001/human_STARindex/ \
     --genomeFastaFiles /scratchLocal/ifa4001/human.fa \
     --sjdbGTFfile /scratchLocal/ifa4001/human.gtf \
     --sjdbOverhang 49
exit

According to the STAR2.7.0 manual, the following parameters must be considered:

–runThreadN NumberOfThreads (this defines the number of threads to be used for genome generation, it has to be set to the number of available cores on the server node, so this should be one )

–runMode genomeGenerate (standard for genome index generation)

–genomeDir /path/to/genomeDir (human genome directory)

–genomeFastaFiles /path/to/genome/fasta (unzipped fasta file)

–sjdbGTFfile /path/to/annotations.gtf (unzipped annotation file)

–sjdbOverhang ReadLength-1 (the read length for my experiment was 50 bp, so the sjdbOverhang should be 49)

Alignment

I used the following bash script (/project/STAR_align_2)

#! /bin/bash -l
#SBATCH --partition=angsd_class
#SBATCH --nodes=2
#SBATCH --ntasks=4
#SBATCH --job-name=STARalign
#SBATCH --time=12:00:00
#SBATCH --mem=60G
spack load star@2.7.0e
for sample in KO_2D10_1 KO_2D10_2 KO_2D10_3 KO_2D9_1 KO_2D9_2 KO_2D9_3 WT_2C11_1 WT_2C11_2 WT_2C11_3; do
  STAR -- runMode alignReads \
       -- outFilterMultimapNmax 3 \
       -- runThreadN 4 \
       -- genomeDir human_STARindex \
       -- readFilesIn RNAseq_IA_fastq/HEK293T_SHPRH_${sample}_R1_001.fastq.gz RNAseq_IA_fastq/HEK293T_SHPRH_${sample}_R2_001.fastq.gz \
       -- readFilesCommand zcat \
       -- outFileNamePrefix aligned/HEK293T_SHPRH_${sample}_aligned. \
       -- outSAMtype BAM SortedByCoordinate
done

Each of my sample were ran in triplicate, and each triplicate was ran across too lanes (files distinguished by R1 and R2 of the same replicate). The syntax used in the script above combines the alignment for the R1 and R2 samples for each replcate.

Due to time constraints, the following report was ran on one technical replicate of one sample condition, SHPRH_KO_2D10_1.

Lastly, I wanted to run multiqc on these files to assess the quality of this single alignment.

Script to run un multiqc on HEK293T_SHPRH_KO_2D10_1

spack load -r py-multiqc
multiqc aligned

Visualization of multiqc

STAR Alignment Scores: Number of Reads

The plot above indicates that 91.2% of my reads were uniquely mapped, 5.1% were mapped to multiple loci, and 1.9% were ampped to “too many loci.” I am not sure if this is a concern moving forward, but I am curious to see what the rest of my samples look like. According to this preliminary alignment and QC, I believe that my raw data files will yield good quality results moving forward.
